WEBVTT

00:03.693 --> 00:07.076
- These night shifts
have got me tired.

00:07.110 --> 00:08.836
- Well, we've got
four more hours.

00:08.870 --> 00:10.217
Keep it together.
- Yes, sir.

00:10.251 --> 00:13.392
Sorry, it's just,
a week of nights and I--

00:13.427 --> 00:15.429
I still can't get
my circadian rhythm in line.

00:15.463 --> 00:17.224
And forget about
altering my chronotype

00:17.258 --> 00:19.743
to maximize sleep efficiency.

00:19.778 --> 00:21.021
- Well, perhaps
it's for the best,

00:21.055 --> 00:22.470
seeing as how
we're getting back on days

00:22.505 --> 00:24.024
now that I finally
paid back everyone

00:24.058 --> 00:25.197
who covered for me
while I was gone.

00:25.232 --> 00:26.854
- Hm.
[door buzzes]

00:26.888 --> 00:28.062
- Forgetting anything?

00:30.237 --> 00:31.583
- I don't think so.
- You sure?

00:33.964 --> 00:35.311
- 100% sure.
- Good.

00:35.345 --> 00:36.829
How about the suspect?

00:36.864 --> 00:40.350
- ♪ Whoa, oh, oh,
oh, oh, oh, oh ♪

00:40.385 --> 00:42.594
♪ I'm gonna win for you

00:42.628 --> 00:46.011
♪ Like I know
you want me to do ♪

00:46.046 --> 00:48.255
[music playing softly]

00:48.289 --> 00:49.394
[door opens]

00:49.428 --> 00:50.360
- Hey.

00:50.395 --> 00:51.223
- Hi.

00:53.191 --> 00:54.985
- Is that a present for me?

00:55.020 --> 00:56.573
- Yep. And the beer's for me.

00:56.608 --> 00:58.023
- Thank you.

01:01.578 --> 01:03.132
- What?

01:03.166 --> 01:06.583
- Nothing.
I'm--it's just, um,

01:06.618 --> 01:09.379
gift giving isn't really
your love language, so...

01:09.414 --> 01:11.174
- Oh, yeah.

01:11.209 --> 01:12.486
What is my love language?

01:12.520 --> 01:14.660
- Terse nods, mainly.

01:14.695 --> 01:16.869
- Okay, well, I'm trying
to change things up.

01:16.904 --> 01:18.354
- Okay.
Well, can I open it now?

01:18.388 --> 01:19.769
- Yeah, of course.

01:23.738 --> 01:25.326
- Oh, my God.

01:25.361 --> 01:27.501
My killed-in-action radio?

01:27.535 --> 01:28.571
Aww.

01:28.605 --> 01:30.297
That is so sweet.

01:30.331 --> 01:31.574
- Well, it gave its life
for yours,

01:31.608 --> 01:34.024
so I thought it'd be nice
to memorialize your effort

01:34.059 --> 01:35.991
in the Jeff Budny takedown.

01:36.026 --> 01:37.097
- Thank you.

01:39.133 --> 01:41.929
- Oops.
I-I forgot it was date night.

01:41.963 --> 01:42.895
I will hide in my room.

01:42.930 --> 01:44.896
- You don't have to do that.

01:44.932 --> 01:46.209
- No, it's my bad.

01:46.244 --> 01:48.073
What smells so good?
- Paella.

01:48.108 --> 01:49.419
You want me to make you a plate

01:49.454 --> 01:51.420
for your room?
[cell phone buzzes]

01:51.456 --> 01:52.698
- I would say no,
but I'd be lying.

01:52.733 --> 01:54.666
- [laughs]

01:54.700 --> 01:55.701
- Yep, Bradford.

01:55.735 --> 01:56.806
Who's this?

01:59.188 --> 02:00.913
Understood.
I'll be there in 20.

02:00.948 --> 02:02.087
- What's going on?

02:02.122 --> 02:03.157
- I gotta go, sorry.

02:03.192 --> 02:04.158
- Just wait--
- I can't.

02:04.193 --> 02:05.332
I'll call you when I can.

02:05.366 --> 02:09.128
[ominous music]

02:11.338 --> 02:12.304
- What just happened?

02:12.339 --> 02:14.030
- I don't know.

02:14.064 --> 02:16.170
- Can I do
a vodka soda, please?

02:16.204 --> 02:19.415
[upbeat music playing]

02:19.449 --> 02:22.038
Dr. London?

02:22.072 --> 02:23.591
- Hi.

02:23.626 --> 02:25.075
Uh--
- It's okay.

02:25.110 --> 02:27.319
I know, uh, seeing a patient
in the wild is tricky.

02:27.353 --> 02:29.218
- Sorry, I just had
a whole semester

02:29.252 --> 02:31.220
of ethics classes
flash through my mind.

02:31.254 --> 02:33.498
But if you're okay talking
out in the wild...

02:33.531 --> 02:35.189
- Totally. May I?

02:35.224 --> 02:37.329
- Mm-hmm.

02:37.364 --> 02:39.020
So do you live around here?

02:39.055 --> 02:40.884
- No, I actually live
on the West Side.

02:40.918 --> 02:42.541
I just got done seeing a movie
around the corner,

02:42.576 --> 02:44.578
and, uh, came in here
for a little nightcap.

02:44.612 --> 02:45.889
- Drinking alone?

02:45.924 --> 02:46.890
- Yeah, but, you know,
I kind of look at it

02:46.925 --> 02:48.375
as a sign of self-assurance,

02:48.409 --> 02:50.170
not so much a cry for help.

02:50.204 --> 02:51.826
What about you?

02:51.861 --> 02:56.383
- I...I got stood up.

02:56.417 --> 02:58.212
- Who the hell
would stand you up?

02:58.247 --> 02:59.731
I mean, you are a catch
and then some.

02:59.765 --> 03:01.042
- [laughs]

03:01.077 --> 03:02.389
- Sorry, that's inappropriate.

03:02.423 --> 03:03.493
- Completely.

03:03.528 --> 03:05.702
But my ego
really appreciated it.

03:09.499 --> 03:11.984
Okay. I should go.

03:12.019 --> 03:14.987
- Yeah.
Or I could buy you a drink.

03:15.022 --> 03:18.474
In a total, like,
patient-doctor kind of way.

03:18.508 --> 03:19.853
- I really shouldn't.

03:19.889 --> 03:21.131
- Right.

03:22.547 --> 03:23.513
- One drink.

03:23.548 --> 03:24.514
- All right, deal.

03:24.549 --> 03:25.722
What you drinking?

03:25.757 --> 03:28.346
[distant barking]

03:38.045 --> 03:39.184
[door clicks open]

03:41.013 --> 03:42.360
- What's up, man?
Thanks for coming.

03:42.394 --> 03:43.533
- I had no choice.

03:43.567 --> 03:44.845
If Ray's alive,
we got a problem.

03:44.879 --> 03:46.053
- He is.
I'm sure.

03:46.087 --> 03:47.192
- How?

03:47.227 --> 03:49.194
They found the tags, his DNA.

03:49.228 --> 03:50.575
We saw the air strike.
There's no one who could have

03:50.609 --> 03:51.886
walked away
from something like that.

03:51.921 --> 03:53.302
- Yeah, that's
what I thought too.

03:53.336 --> 03:54.820
But then a few years ago,
I started hearing stories,

03:54.855 --> 03:56.270
that he was still alive,

03:56.305 --> 03:57.823
working as a gun for hire
around the globe.

03:57.858 --> 04:00.585
So I set up some trip wires
just to be sure.

04:00.619 --> 04:04.105
That's Ray coming
through LAX yesterday.

04:04.140 --> 04:05.521
- What the hell's
he doing here?

04:05.555 --> 04:07.177
- His mom's dying of cancer.

04:07.212 --> 04:08.696
- So she's who
we're staking out?

04:08.731 --> 04:11.665
- Two houses up on the left.
No sign of Ray yet.

04:11.699 --> 04:13.632
- So when did Ray give a crap
about anybody but himself?

04:13.667 --> 04:14.806
- Doesn't matter.

04:14.840 --> 04:17.221
We made a promise.

04:17.257 --> 04:18.637
- That was a long time ago.

04:18.672 --> 04:20.915
- Time doesn't erase
what he did.

04:20.950 --> 04:23.021
Time doesn't bring back
our friends that he killed.

04:23.055 --> 04:26.680
And we made a vow that
if by some miracle he survived,

04:26.714 --> 04:29.234
we'd kill him.

04:29.269 --> 04:30.856
And I am here
to honor that promise.

04:33.721 --> 04:37.380
- Most of these men could be
my dad, some my grandpa.

04:37.415 --> 04:41.108
But I'm supposed to be
some sort of authority figure.

04:41.142 --> 04:44.076
I have cereal for dinner
at least three nights a week.

04:44.111 --> 04:46.527
- Oh. So do I.

04:46.562 --> 04:48.080
- Mine has
dehydrated marshmallows.

04:48.115 --> 04:49.496
- Okay, see, that is a problem.

04:49.530 --> 04:50.531
- [chuckles]

04:50.566 --> 04:51.567
- [chuckles]

04:56.779 --> 04:59.229
I should go.

04:59.264 --> 05:01.577
- Yeah.
Uh, time to call an Uber.

05:01.611 --> 05:03.924
- I mean, I could
give you a ride.

05:03.958 --> 05:04.994
- Really?

05:05.028 --> 05:07.376
- Yeah, it's not a problem.

05:07.410 --> 05:08.377
- Okay.

05:08.411 --> 05:09.343
- Cool.

05:11.138 --> 05:12.657
- This is me.

05:12.691 --> 05:15.453
[music playing over radio]

05:17.938 --> 05:18.697
Thanks for the ride.

05:18.732 --> 05:20.181
- Yeah, no problem.

05:20.216 --> 05:21.321
[door clicks open]

05:24.531 --> 05:25.601
- Good night.

05:33.885 --> 05:35.818
[gunshots, sirens wailing]

05:35.852 --> 05:38.407
- 7-Adam-15, multiple callers
report shots fired,

05:38.441 --> 05:40.409
715 Sycamore.

05:40.443 --> 05:43.135
No associated vehicles.
I'll attach two more units.

05:46.794 --> 05:47.830
- You got here quick.

05:47.864 --> 05:48.865
- We were finishing up a call

05:48.900 --> 05:50.384
around the corner,
heard the shots.

05:50.419 --> 05:52.041
- All right, this is
as far as you go.

05:52.075 --> 05:53.663
- We'll stage here
until you Code 4 it.

05:53.698 --> 05:55.182
Be safe.
- Right.

05:56.494 --> 05:58.047
Follow me.

06:00.774 --> 06:02.223
All right, be alert.

06:02.258 --> 06:03.224
I know you're tired.

06:03.259 --> 06:04.329
- Well, not anymore.

06:04.364 --> 06:05.710
Adrenaline is flowing.

06:05.744 --> 06:07.125
- Good. Let's do this.

06:13.062 --> 06:15.651
[tense music]

06:15.685 --> 06:22.727
♪

06:28.526 --> 06:29.492
Juarez.

06:37.500 --> 06:38.639
Go.

06:38.674 --> 06:45.439
♪

06:47.234 --> 06:49.478
- What happened here?

06:49.512 --> 06:52.066
- Control, 7-Adam-15,
two victims, gunshot wounds.

06:52.101 --> 06:53.240
Still clearing house.

06:53.274 --> 06:55.449
[breathing heavily]

06:55.484 --> 06:57.313
I'll take left. Go.

06:57.347 --> 07:04.216
♪

07:05.839 --> 07:08.151
- [gurgles]
- Officer Nolan!

07:08.186 --> 07:09.498
Hey, ambulance
is right outside.

07:09.532 --> 07:10.533
Stay with me.

07:14.951 --> 07:16.712
- 7-Adam-15,
residence is cleared.

07:16.746 --> 07:18.196
Code 4 for fire.

07:18.230 --> 07:20.992
One gunshot wound victim
is unconscious but breathing.

07:21.026 --> 07:22.096
How is she?
- Her pulse is weak.

07:22.131 --> 07:23.097
She could bleed out.

07:23.132 --> 07:24.720
- John?
- Back here.

07:26.929 --> 07:28.724
She's the only one left alive.

07:33.038 --> 07:34.074
[loud thud]

07:37.526 --> 07:38.492
You didn't clear the closet?

07:38.527 --> 07:39.907
- Uh, no.

07:39.942 --> 07:42.531
- Police. Come out now.

07:42.565 --> 07:47.190
♪

07:47.225 --> 07:48.571
- [whimpers]

07:48.606 --> 07:51.159
- Oh. Hey.

07:51.194 --> 07:53.334
What are you doing in here?

07:53.369 --> 07:55.682
Come here.
Come here, little one.

07:55.716 --> 07:57.683
[sirens wailing,
helicopter whirring]

07:57.718 --> 07:59.064
What are you doing?

08:00.721 --> 08:03.344
Yeah, I'm sorry.
Hey, look at this.

08:03.379 --> 08:04.725
You don't need
to see that, okay?

08:09.109 --> 08:11.007
- How's the mother?
- Still in surgery.

08:11.042 --> 08:12.215
They're checking in
on the little girl.

08:12.250 --> 08:13.562
No visible injuries.

08:13.596 --> 08:15.978
- Yeah, her first name is Anna,
last name Hughes.

08:16.012 --> 08:17.669
Remi's the mom, Ellis the dad,

08:17.704 --> 08:20.189
and the older woman in the
dining room was Grandma Debra.

08:20.223 --> 08:21.431
- You think the girl saw
what happened?

08:21.466 --> 08:22.432
- Oh, I hope not.

08:22.467 --> 08:23.882
She still hasn't said a word.

08:23.917 --> 08:25.919
- I've been in contact
with CPS.

08:25.953 --> 08:28.024
They are searching for a family
member to come to the hospital

08:28.059 --> 08:29.992
and take custody of Anna
once she's cleared.

08:30.026 --> 08:32.235
- You know, we still have
a whole lot of paperwork to do.

08:32.270 --> 08:34.236
We'll probably stick around,
see how the surgery goes.

08:34.272 --> 08:35.860
- Of course. I'll let you know
if anything changes.

08:35.894 --> 08:37.240
- Thank you.

08:37.275 --> 08:38.897
- Keep me updated
to the minute on this.

08:38.932 --> 08:40.623
A family murdered
in the middle of the night

08:40.658 --> 08:42.486
is gonna keep a lot
of people on edge.

08:42.522 --> 08:43.592
- Yes, sir.

08:48.735 --> 08:53.533
Now, about you not searching
the closet.

08:53.567 --> 08:55.845
- There's no excuse, sir.
I-I saw the injured woman,

08:55.880 --> 08:57.157
and I put her as a priority

08:57.191 --> 08:58.641
before I finished
clearing the room.

08:58.676 --> 08:59.918
It won't happen again.

08:59.953 --> 09:01.575
- See that it doesn't.

09:01.610 --> 09:04.509
If that was the shooter
in there instead of a child,

09:04.544 --> 09:06.442
we'd both be dead.

09:06.476 --> 09:09.445
[somber music]

09:09.479 --> 09:16.279
♪

09:26.048 --> 09:28.913
[line trills]

09:28.947 --> 09:30.708
- It's Bradford.
You know what to do.

09:30.742 --> 09:32.537
- Hey, it's me.

09:32.572 --> 09:35.160
Um, no idea
where you are right now,

09:35.195 --> 09:37.542
but, uh, I'm here
if you need me.

09:37.577 --> 09:40.407
So just call me when you can.

09:45.619 --> 09:46.965
[cell phone buzzes]

09:47.000 --> 09:51.867
♪

09:51.901 --> 09:53.696
- [sighs]

10:02.567 --> 10:04.086
- Yeah, there's a back door,
but you gotta go

10:04.120 --> 10:05.570
through the neighbor's yard
to get to it.

10:05.605 --> 10:07.192
And there's no way
to see if Ray's inside.

10:07.227 --> 10:08.918
- And--and if he is?
Then what?

10:08.953 --> 10:10.886
We hog-tie him
and dump him in deep water?

10:10.920 --> 10:12.266
- Well, I was thinking
landfill,

10:12.301 --> 10:13.682
but if you got a boat--
- This isn't funny.

10:13.716 --> 10:15.269
Just talking about this
is criminal conspiracy.

10:15.304 --> 10:18.031
- I never would have thought
the Reaper would go soft on me.

10:18.065 --> 10:20.136
- I ain't going soft.

10:20.171 --> 10:21.655
That pact was made
a long time ago

10:21.690 --> 10:22.829
in the anger and fog of war.

10:22.863 --> 10:25.417
But now...[sighs]

10:25.452 --> 10:26.971
I'm a cop.

10:27.005 --> 10:27.868
You're an army lawyer.

10:27.903 --> 10:29.490
We've built lives.

10:29.525 --> 10:31.561
- Yeah, well, what about
Henderson and Coyle?

10:31.596 --> 10:34.357
They never got to build
their lives 'cause of Ray.

10:34.392 --> 10:36.325
They deserve justice.

10:36.359 --> 10:38.638
And we owe that to them.

10:42.124 --> 10:43.573
- You okay?

10:43.608 --> 10:46.024
- I wasn't much older
when my dad died.

10:46.059 --> 10:47.750
Do you think she knows?

10:47.785 --> 10:49.027
- I-I don't know.

10:49.062 --> 10:50.684
Do you think
she'd even understand?

10:50.719 --> 10:52.237
- I don't know.
- Ah.

10:52.272 --> 10:53.583
- Her mother's out of surgery.

10:53.618 --> 10:55.137
She flatlined on the table,

10:55.171 --> 10:56.483
but they were able
to get her back.

10:56.517 --> 10:57.967
She's still very much
in the woods.

10:58.002 --> 10:59.348
- Any luck finding a relative?

10:59.382 --> 11:01.005
- There's no immediate family
in Los Angeles,

11:01.039 --> 11:03.593
but CPS is gonna widen
the search in the morning.

11:03.628 --> 11:04.871
- So what happens to her now?

11:04.905 --> 11:07.390
- And please don't say
children's shelter.

11:07.425 --> 11:09.013
- For the short term, yes.

11:09.047 --> 11:11.360
And if there's no relative
found, then foster care.

11:11.394 --> 11:12.913
- Those shelters can be grim.

11:12.948 --> 11:15.019
They're chaotic,
underfunded, understaffed.

11:15.053 --> 11:16.227
- I agree.

11:16.261 --> 11:18.816
Not the most ideal place
for a toddler

11:18.850 --> 11:20.887
who just lived through
her family getting slaughtered.

11:20.921 --> 11:22.716
- Give me a second.

11:22.751 --> 11:24.200
I got him.
I'll get him.

11:24.235 --> 11:25.546
Oh, he landed on his butt.

11:25.581 --> 11:27.894
There we go.

11:27.928 --> 11:29.723
He's all better.

11:29.758 --> 11:31.000
Got him?
Here you go.

11:33.209 --> 11:34.176
What do you think?

11:34.210 --> 11:36.143
- About what?

11:36.178 --> 11:37.835
- I'll be right back.

11:43.910 --> 11:46.222
What about Anna staying
with us tonight?

11:46.257 --> 11:47.568
- We aren't registered
foster parents.

11:47.603 --> 11:48.846
It's a process.

11:48.880 --> 11:51.503
- I'm aware,
but we're first responders.

11:51.538 --> 11:53.678
I'm sure CPS would
sign off on it.

11:53.713 --> 11:55.231
Anything's better than
those children's shelters.

11:55.266 --> 11:57.199
- I don't know about that.

11:57.233 --> 12:00.029
- It would be for one night,
or until they find a relative

12:00.064 --> 12:02.066
or a temporary
foster situation.

12:02.100 --> 12:03.101
- But...[sighs]

12:04.689 --> 12:05.690
- But what?

12:08.555 --> 12:09.867
- Nothing.

12:09.901 --> 12:11.247
You're right.

12:11.282 --> 12:12.559
- You won't regret this.

12:12.593 --> 12:13.698
Luna.

12:15.182 --> 12:18.427
What about Anna coming home
with us tonight?

12:18.461 --> 12:20.049
- I don't see why not.

12:20.084 --> 12:21.395
I'll go start
making some calls,

12:21.430 --> 12:22.465
see if we can make it happen.

12:25.054 --> 12:26.884
- Just like
the good old days, huh?

12:26.918 --> 12:29.334
Staking out a potential target,
hours and hours of nothing.

12:29.369 --> 12:30.680
- Just your bad jokes.

12:30.715 --> 12:32.786
- Hey, those jokes were
me training to be a dad.

12:32.821 --> 12:34.754
I got two now, Scott and Nancy.

12:34.788 --> 12:36.410
Best kids ever.

12:36.445 --> 12:37.860
- Yeah, must take after
their mother.

12:37.895 --> 12:39.206
- [chuckles]

12:40.898 --> 12:42.415
- We got movement.

12:42.451 --> 12:44.902
- Was that Ray or his mom?

12:44.936 --> 12:46.489
- Let's go find out.

12:46.524 --> 12:47.490
- Hey, you think
that's a good idea?

12:47.525 --> 12:49.320
[door closes]

12:49.354 --> 12:53.013
[tense music]

12:53.048 --> 12:54.325
[knocks on door]

12:54.359 --> 12:59.502
♪

12:59.537 --> 13:00.780
- What do you want?

13:00.814 --> 13:02.678
- Mrs. Watkins,
I'm Sergeant Tim Bradford.

13:02.712 --> 13:04.197
This is Major Mark Greer.

13:04.231 --> 13:05.370
We'd like to talk to you
about your son.

13:05.405 --> 13:06.993
- Well, he's dead.

13:07.027 --> 13:08.718
What else do you need to know?

13:08.753 --> 13:10.134
- Do you mind if we come inside
for a second to talk?

13:10.168 --> 13:11.411
- I do mind.

13:11.445 --> 13:12.895
- We served with Ray, ma'am.

13:12.930 --> 13:14.759
We just need a moment
of your time.

13:16.761 --> 13:17.900
- Ugh.

13:22.422 --> 13:25.252
Well, make it quick.

13:25.287 --> 13:26.875
I'm not long for this life,

13:26.909 --> 13:28.877
and I don't want to waste
what's left with you two.

13:28.911 --> 13:30.326
- I'm so sorry to hear about

13:30.361 --> 13:31.051
what you've been
going through, ma'am.

13:31.086 --> 13:32.915
I lost my mom to cancer.

13:32.950 --> 13:35.331
- Trust me, she's better off.

13:38.369 --> 13:40.716
- Would you mind
if I use the bathroom?

13:40.750 --> 13:41.890
- Down the hall.

13:41.924 --> 13:43.098
- Thanks.

13:48.448 --> 13:51.761
[tense music]

13:51.796 --> 13:58.596
♪

14:30.731 --> 14:31.905
- Bradford,
you don't need that.

14:31.940 --> 14:33.734
That, uh--
- [exhales]

14:33.769 --> 14:35.391
- What's wrong?

14:35.426 --> 14:37.221
You look like
you've seen a ghost.

14:38.739 --> 14:39.913
Yo, Greer.

14:39.948 --> 14:42.640
My God, man, you got old.

14:44.159 --> 14:45.954
- I just told them
you were dead.

14:45.988 --> 14:47.300
Now you made me look
like an idiot.

14:47.334 --> 14:48.646
- Calm down.

14:48.680 --> 14:50.027
You don't look like an idiot.

14:50.061 --> 14:53.030
Mom, why don't you, um,
give us a minute, huh?

14:55.066 --> 14:57.655
- You're gonna cry when I die.

14:57.689 --> 14:58.898
- We'll see.

15:02.177 --> 15:06.146
[sighs]
So...

15:06.181 --> 15:09.391
what are you two doing
at a dead guy's house, huh?

15:09.425 --> 15:10.702
- Bring you to justice.

15:10.737 --> 15:12.394
- Oh, yeah?
For what?

15:12.428 --> 15:13.982
- For starters, being AWOL,

15:14.016 --> 15:16.363
faking your own death,
felony grand theft.

15:16.398 --> 15:18.538
You stole at least $1/2 million
from the U.S. government.

15:18.572 --> 15:20.920
- Can you blame me?
I mean, the CIA was giving away

15:20.954 --> 15:22.473
backpacks of cash.

15:22.507 --> 15:23.681
No one was gonna miss it.

15:23.715 --> 15:24.854
- You called in an air strike

15:24.889 --> 15:26.718
on your own guys
when we came for you.

15:26.753 --> 15:27.927
There wasn't enough
of Coyle and Henderson

15:27.961 --> 15:28.997
to fit in a shoebox.

15:29.031 --> 15:32.172
- That sounds really bad.

15:33.967 --> 15:36.521
But I know that's not true.
Do you know how I know that?

15:36.556 --> 15:40.387
Because I read
the after action report

15:40.422 --> 15:45.151
that was signed
by the two of you.

15:45.185 --> 15:46.876
- The only reason
the report reads that way

15:46.911 --> 15:48.154
is so that your wife
and daughter

15:48.188 --> 15:50.466
could get your death benefits.

15:50.501 --> 15:52.537
[knife clatters]

15:52.572 --> 15:55.333
- I never asked for that.

15:55.368 --> 15:59.234
You knew she was about a month
away from "Dear John"-ing me.

15:59.268 --> 16:01.891
But thanks
to your bleeding hearts,

16:01.926 --> 16:03.169
I'm now untouchable.

16:03.203 --> 16:04.722
I mean, you bring me
in right now,

16:04.756 --> 16:07.069
you've got to tell Uncle Sam
about your big lie, right?

16:07.104 --> 16:08.864
And you'll, what,
be retroactively

16:08.898 --> 16:11.315
dishonorably discharged
and most likely

16:11.349 --> 16:12.764
get fired
from your current jobs.

16:12.799 --> 16:15.008
So you can arrest me,
it's okay.

16:15.043 --> 16:16.078
Come on.

16:17.977 --> 16:19.254
Here I am.

16:19.288 --> 16:21.739
No?
Yeah, that's what I thought.

16:21.773 --> 16:25.812
I'm gonna be here
to watch the old lady croak,

16:25.846 --> 16:27.158
and then get back
to what I was doing.

16:27.193 --> 16:30.851
And we are never going
to see each other again.

16:30.886 --> 16:33.061
How does that sound?

16:33.095 --> 16:34.441
Sweet.

16:44.037 --> 16:46.591
[laughs]

16:51.562 --> 16:55.566
Been really great catching up
with my old war buddies.

16:55.600 --> 16:57.154
Greer.

16:57.188 --> 16:59.604
You really do look old as hell.

17:02.538 --> 17:04.713
- That go how you thought
it would, Reaper?

17:04.747 --> 17:06.196
All we accomplished
was letting that guy know

17:06.232 --> 17:07.509
we're coming for him.

17:07.542 --> 17:09.338
Gonna be twice as hard
to take him out now.

17:12.893 --> 17:16.069
- It has been a long time
since I've tucked in a toddler.

17:16.104 --> 17:18.554
- How'd it feel?
- Wonderful.

17:18.589 --> 17:20.660
I do think I tweaked my back
just a little bit.

17:20.694 --> 17:22.558
- Oh, no.

17:22.593 --> 17:25.423
- All right, we are gonna need
to make a list.

17:25.458 --> 17:26.528
- Yes, we are.

17:26.561 --> 17:29.082
We need diapers, baby wipes.

17:29.117 --> 17:30.359
- Food--Cheerios.

17:30.394 --> 17:31.636
Henry loved Cheerios.

17:31.671 --> 17:32.810
Milk--we're out of milk.

17:32.844 --> 17:34.674
- And we need
some baby toys, probably?

17:34.708 --> 17:36.055
- Yeah, definitely toys.

17:36.089 --> 17:38.678
- And we need to do
some babyproofing,

17:38.712 --> 17:40.645
'cause this is dangerous.

17:40.680 --> 17:42.061
- Yeah, okay.

17:42.095 --> 17:44.132
Anything big
should be pulled down.

17:44.166 --> 17:45.926
- Uh, these corners
are really sharp.

17:45.961 --> 17:48.412
- Pointy things, for sure.

17:48.446 --> 17:49.723
I'm regretting
those succulents now.

17:51.587 --> 17:53.658
- How bad do you think this
is gonna screw the kid up?

17:53.693 --> 17:55.143
[camera shutter clicking]

17:55.177 --> 17:58.249
- Depends on what you saw
and where she goes from here.

17:58.284 --> 18:00.665
- Lila was older than Anna
when she saw me get attacked,

18:00.700 --> 18:04.048
but I always wonder how much
of that stayed with her.

18:04.083 --> 18:05.325
- She's one of the most
well-adjusted kids

18:05.360 --> 18:07.016
I've ever met.
You got no worries there.

18:08.777 --> 18:11.193
- Any clarity on the parents?

18:11.228 --> 18:13.333
- Mom had a suspended sentence
for possession.

18:13.368 --> 18:15.370
Went through a diversion
program successfully

18:15.404 --> 18:17.026
and seems to have been clean.

18:17.061 --> 18:18.925
Father was in and out of jail.

18:18.959 --> 18:21.514
Couple drug cases,
one assault charge.

18:21.548 --> 18:23.516
- Is this their past
coming back?

18:23.550 --> 18:26.139
- Maybe.
Although they seemed

18:26.174 --> 18:27.589
to turn things around
since Anna arrived.

18:27.623 --> 18:31.558
Both parents were employed,
kept their noses clean.

18:31.593 --> 18:33.940
- All right, we should dig
into their financials.

18:33.974 --> 18:36.149
Things might have gotten tight
with the kid in the picture.

18:36.184 --> 18:38.324
Maybe the dad had
to reach back out

18:38.358 --> 18:40.049
to some of his friends
in the drug business.

18:41.327 --> 18:42.707
- Oh, uh, what's that?

18:42.742 --> 18:43.915
- Oh, it's Blair's jacket.

18:43.950 --> 18:45.848
She left it in my car
last night.

18:45.883 --> 18:48.057
Oh, do you mind if we, um, stop
by her office to drop it off?

18:48.092 --> 18:49.162
- Who's Blair?

18:49.197 --> 18:50.819
- My therapist.

18:50.853 --> 18:52.372
- You went out
with your therapist last night?

18:52.407 --> 18:53.822
- No, we ran into each other.
It was just a drink.

18:53.856 --> 18:55.720
Totally innocent.

18:55.755 --> 18:57.515
Although I was picking up
some vibes.

18:57.550 --> 18:59.483
- That crosses so many lines.

18:59.517 --> 19:01.209
You--you know that you're
not supposed to go out

19:01.243 --> 19:02.589
with your therapist, right?

19:02.624 --> 19:03.728
- Well, me and Lil' Gurkin
used to hang out

19:03.763 --> 19:04.936
with Dr. Shrink all the time.

19:04.971 --> 19:06.731
- Lil'--D--
so wait, wait, wait, what?

19:06.766 --> 19:08.526
- Dr. Shrink.
That was my last therapist.

19:08.561 --> 19:09.907
That's just what we called him.
- Okay.

19:09.941 --> 19:11.288
And was this therapist
licensed?

19:11.322 --> 19:13.497
[quirky percussive music]

19:13.531 --> 19:16.293
- No.
- What? [chuckles]

19:16.327 --> 19:19.330
- Hey, you think Blair left her
jacket in my car on purpose?

19:19.365 --> 19:20.573
Like, to have an excuse
to see me again?

19:20.607 --> 19:22.851
- She does have an excuse
to see you again.

19:22.885 --> 19:25.094
Therapy.

19:25.129 --> 19:26.889
- Yeah.
[engine turns over]

19:26.924 --> 19:28.581
- She is adorable.

19:28.615 --> 19:30.755
- She really is.

19:30.790 --> 19:32.861
- You know, when your child
grows up and leaves,

19:32.895 --> 19:34.897
you don't just miss them.

19:34.932 --> 19:37.728
You miss all
the versions of them

19:37.762 --> 19:39.868
like they're all these separate
individual people.

19:39.902 --> 19:42.077
You miss the--
the infant version,

19:42.111 --> 19:44.804
the toddler version,
the skinny 10-year-old version.

19:44.838 --> 19:46.668
And then the man
that Henry's become.

19:46.702 --> 19:48.635
- That's why people keep
having kids,

19:48.670 --> 19:50.361
to get back to those versions
they miss.

19:50.396 --> 19:51.535
[knock on door]
- Oh.

19:51.569 --> 19:53.399
They should develop
a time machine.

19:53.433 --> 19:55.470
It'd certainly make
things simpler.

19:55.504 --> 19:56.643
- Mm. And cheaper.

19:56.678 --> 19:58.058
- And cheaper.

19:59.922 --> 20:01.269
Ah, it's Luna.
- Mm.

20:03.926 --> 20:06.412
- Hey. Nice to see ya.
- Hey.

20:06.446 --> 20:08.414
- What's--what's wrong?

20:08.448 --> 20:12.072
- Anna's mom, Remi,
she died a little while ago.

20:12.107 --> 20:14.316
[bouncy kids' music playing]

20:14.351 --> 20:16.145
- [exhales heavily]
- [coos]

20:19.942 --> 20:20.909
- So what happens now?

20:20.943 --> 20:22.462
- We don't have great options.

20:22.497 --> 20:24.257
She'll end up at a shelter
for a week or two

20:24.292 --> 20:25.741
until we can find
a foster family

20:25.776 --> 20:27.985
that will take her in.

20:28.019 --> 20:30.194
Unless--
- Unless what?

20:30.229 --> 20:32.403
- Unless you would be willing
to keep her

20:32.438 --> 20:34.094
until we can place her
with a family.

20:36.062 --> 20:37.581
- What do you think about that?

20:37.615 --> 20:39.065
- I think that's a bad idea.

20:41.343 --> 20:43.000
- Would you give us
a minute, please?

20:43.034 --> 20:44.208
- Of course.

20:46.693 --> 20:48.005
- What's going on?
- Nothing.

20:48.039 --> 20:49.386
- No, not nothing.

20:49.420 --> 20:52.009
Any other day,
you are generous to a fault.

20:52.043 --> 20:53.562
- Well, it's--
it's not about that.

20:53.597 --> 20:55.564
I-I want what's best for Anna.

20:55.599 --> 20:58.464
And I think bonding with us
for a few weeks is only gonna

20:58.498 --> 21:00.397
damage her further
on the back end

21:00.431 --> 21:02.675
when, you know,
they pull her away from us.

21:02.709 --> 21:05.125
- Okay. Maybe.

21:06.610 --> 21:09.026
But that's not really
why you're hesitating, is it?

21:10.924 --> 21:13.375
- When I was 15,
I was babysitting

21:13.410 --> 21:16.689
for my four-year-old
neighbor, Ryan.

21:16.723 --> 21:18.553
I got distracted for a second.

21:18.587 --> 21:22.729
And when I turned around,
he was in the pool.

21:22.764 --> 21:25.663
I jumped in.
I pulled him out.

21:25.698 --> 21:26.837
He was fine.

21:26.871 --> 21:30.012
But ever since then...

21:30.047 --> 21:33.740
I was almost the reason
my neighbors lost their son.

21:33.775 --> 21:35.155
I'm not mom material.

21:35.190 --> 21:39.263
- Okay.
Um, I disagree.

21:39.298 --> 21:41.472
But I understand.

21:41.507 --> 21:44.337
Let's just say goodbye to Anna.

21:46.512 --> 21:47.720
- Wait.

21:50.378 --> 21:52.518
Okay.
- Are you sure?

21:52.552 --> 21:54.278
I don't want to do this
if you're not comfortable.

21:54.313 --> 21:56.073
- How can I make this about me

21:56.107 --> 21:58.178
after everything
she's been through?

22:01.216 --> 22:05.358
Luna, we will take Anna
until you find a family member

22:05.393 --> 22:07.222
or a good foster home.
- That's amazing.

22:07.256 --> 22:08.913
[cell phone buzzes]
You're amazing for doing this.

22:08.948 --> 22:10.190
- Oh, sorry, this is Wesley.

22:10.225 --> 22:11.813
I'm just gonna grab this.
- Yeah.

22:11.847 --> 22:12.710
- Hey, what's up?

22:12.745 --> 22:14.229
- Uh, "what's up?"

22:14.263 --> 22:15.851
it's your deposition today,
Oscar's lawsuit.

22:15.886 --> 22:18.475
- Wesley, I completely forgot.
I am so sorry.

22:18.509 --> 22:19.890
- Okay, I need you to start
putting these things

22:19.924 --> 22:20.822
in your calendar.
- I am.

22:20.856 --> 22:22.030
I did. I have.

22:22.064 --> 22:23.411
It's--it is.
I just--

22:23.445 --> 22:25.205
I-I have so much going on.

22:25.240 --> 22:27.069
- Look, it's clearly
a frivolous case,

22:27.104 --> 22:28.174
but until I can
get it dismissed,

22:28.208 --> 22:29.486
you need
to take this seriously.

22:29.520 --> 22:30.556
- No, you're absolutely right.

22:30.590 --> 22:32.489
I-I am on my way.

22:32.523 --> 22:34.076
Crap.

22:34.111 --> 22:36.009
Oscar's deposition, I forgot.

22:36.044 --> 22:37.079
It should only take
a couple of hours.

22:37.114 --> 22:38.357
I'm so sorry to leave you.

22:38.391 --> 22:39.392
- It's fine. It's fine.
- Are you sure?

22:39.427 --> 22:40.807
I could try
to take her with me.

22:40.842 --> 22:42.222
- Yeah, don't be silly.
We'll be fine.

22:42.257 --> 22:44.708
And I really want
this Oscar situation behind us.

22:44.742 --> 22:45.847
- You and me both.

22:49.885 --> 22:52.371
- Thorsen, Chen,
what's happenin'?

22:52.405 --> 22:53.855
- Smitty, I'm pretty sure
you're not supposed

22:53.889 --> 22:55.926
to be getting in therapy
while you're on shift.

22:55.960 --> 22:57.341
- Oh, I'm not a patient here.

22:57.376 --> 22:59.205
It's where I come
to take my breaks.

22:59.239 --> 23:01.345
Plus, they got
top-notch snackage

23:01.380 --> 23:04.072
and the mood is super zen.

23:04.106 --> 23:06.246
- Yeah, pretty sure
that's not okay either.

23:06.281 --> 23:07.696
- Tomato, to-mah-to.

23:07.731 --> 23:09.457
- Snackage.
[laughs]

23:09.491 --> 23:10.837
- That's a new one.
- Yeah, I know.

23:10.872 --> 23:12.218
- Officer Thorsen?

23:13.737 --> 23:15.359
I don't have an appointment
with you today, do I?

23:15.394 --> 23:17.844
- No, I just, uh,
brought you your jacket.

23:17.879 --> 23:19.674
- Oh, you didn't have
to do that.

23:19.708 --> 23:20.916
You could have just brought it
to our next session.

23:20.951 --> 23:22.539
- Thought you might need it.

23:22.573 --> 23:24.472
Never know, it might be
your favorite jacket.

23:24.506 --> 23:26.025
- [chuckles dryly]
Thanks.

23:26.059 --> 23:27.267
That was nice of you.

23:30.926 --> 23:31.962
[door closes]

23:33.273 --> 23:35.655
- Okay.
Well, back to work.

23:35.690 --> 23:37.899
- Okay, I'm confused.
[clears throat]

23:37.933 --> 23:39.452
- Are you sure she was
flirting with you last night?

23:39.487 --> 23:40.453
- I thought she was.

23:40.488 --> 23:41.627
- Were you drinking?

23:41.661 --> 23:42.524
- I only had one.

23:42.559 --> 23:44.319
- Oh.

23:44.353 --> 23:46.079
- Oh, no.

23:46.114 --> 23:48.219
Am I that guy?
- What?

23:48.254 --> 23:51.257
- The one that thinks
every girl is hitting on him?

23:51.291 --> 23:52.638
- You know who we could ask?

23:52.672 --> 23:55.572
- Who?
- Celina.

23:55.606 --> 23:56.642
- Funny.
- I know.

23:56.676 --> 23:58.022
- Yeah, funny.
- I'm hilarious.

23:58.057 --> 23:59.023
Bye, Smitty.

23:59.058 --> 24:00.197
- We're not killing him.

24:00.231 --> 24:01.647
- You are looking at this
all wrong.

24:01.681 --> 24:03.096
Ray is already dead.

24:03.131 --> 24:04.581
We're just making sure
he stays that way.

24:04.615 --> 24:06.341
- You can hide behind
that idea all you want,

24:06.375 --> 24:07.584
but we both know
it'll give you no comfort

24:07.618 --> 24:08.585
when the nightmares come.

24:08.619 --> 24:09.620
- So what?

24:09.655 --> 24:10.483
We let him get away with it?

24:10.518 --> 24:12.209
- No.

24:12.243 --> 24:14.176
We come clean--
about everything.

24:14.211 --> 24:16.351
- Not a chance.
Ray is right.

24:16.385 --> 24:18.491
We say anything,
it'll blow up our lives.

24:18.526 --> 24:20.562
I will lose my career,
my family.

24:20.597 --> 24:23.185
- I wouldn't let that happen.
I'll take the fall.

24:23.220 --> 24:24.566
I was squad leader.
It'll all be on me.

24:24.601 --> 24:26.499
- I signed those
after action reports too.

24:26.534 --> 24:27.811
- I'll say I made you sign 'em.

24:27.845 --> 24:30.158
- No one will buy it!

24:30.192 --> 24:32.367
All right, you are gonna
lose everything,

24:32.401 --> 24:36.198
destroy my life, and then
Ray will still be out there.

24:36.233 --> 24:39.995
There is only one way
out of this.

24:40.030 --> 24:42.411
- I can't.

24:42.446 --> 24:44.552
And I won't let you.

24:44.586 --> 24:47.900
- You would arrest me
for killing that scumbag?

24:47.934 --> 24:50.489
[tense music]

24:50.523 --> 24:51.697
- Yes.

24:51.731 --> 24:55.148
♪

24:55.183 --> 24:57.150
- Okay.

24:57.185 --> 24:59.152
Then I'm out.

24:59.187 --> 25:02.052
And whatever death and
destruction Ray causes next,

25:02.086 --> 25:03.812
that's on you.

25:03.847 --> 25:11.061
♪

25:11.095 --> 25:12.372
- [exhales heavily]
[car door closes]

25:16.825 --> 25:18.137
- Well, it's undisputed
that Officer Nolan wanted

25:18.171 --> 25:20.380
to inflict pain
on Oscar Hutchinson.

25:20.415 --> 25:21.485
- Untrue.

25:21.520 --> 25:23.418
It is very much in dispute.

25:23.452 --> 25:26.145
- Are we keeping you up,
Officer Nolan?

25:26.179 --> 25:27.836
Is my client's life
not important to you?

25:27.871 --> 25:29.424
- Sorry, no.

25:29.458 --> 25:31.737
I've been pulling doubles
lately, and last night,

25:31.771 --> 25:33.842
we took home a little girl
whose family had been murdered.

25:33.877 --> 25:35.188
- Please strike that
from the record.

25:35.223 --> 25:37.328
Officer Nolan is clearly
trying to paint himself

25:37.363 --> 25:38.537
in a positive light
for the court.

25:38.571 --> 25:40.746
- Not at all,
though I can understand

25:40.780 --> 25:43.403
how any act of generosity
you would see as manipulative.

25:43.438 --> 25:44.750
- Let's get back on track.

25:44.784 --> 25:47.269
- Yes. Let's.

25:47.304 --> 25:49.996
Officer Nolan, would you read
the highlighted text exchange

25:50.031 --> 25:53.068
from the day of the attack
on Oscar Hutchinson?

25:54.449 --> 25:56.175
- [sighs]

25:56.209 --> 25:58.487
"Why can't this guy just
get shanked in prison?"

25:58.522 --> 26:00.386
- And who did you send
that text to?

26:00.420 --> 26:02.043
- My girlfriend at the time,
Bailey Nune.

26:02.077 --> 26:03.009
- And who were
you referring to?

26:03.044 --> 26:05.529
Who do you wish to see, quote,

26:05.564 --> 26:07.220
"Shanked in prison"?

26:07.255 --> 26:08.256
- I don't wish to see anyone--

26:08.290 --> 26:10.638
- Just answer the question.

26:10.672 --> 26:13.157
Who were you referring to
in the text?

26:13.192 --> 26:14.365
- Oscar Hutchinson.

26:14.400 --> 26:15.919
But this was taken
out of context.

26:15.953 --> 26:18.577
- Under what context do
you wish to see my client dead?

26:18.611 --> 26:19.992
And to what lengths
were you willing to go

26:20.026 --> 26:21.338
to make sure that happened?

26:21.372 --> 26:23.823
- This is just a man
venting his frustration

26:23.858 --> 26:24.893
about work to his wife.

26:24.928 --> 26:26.343
Nothing more.
- Mm.

26:26.377 --> 26:27.655
Let's move on
to the second text,

26:27.689 --> 26:29.760
shall we, Officer Nolan,
if you please?

26:32.625 --> 26:34.558
- Oh, wow.
- Oh, yes.

26:34.593 --> 26:36.871
This is a cool fort,
don't you think?

26:36.905 --> 26:38.389
- Yes.
- And we can feel

26:38.424 --> 26:40.806
really safe in here, huh?

26:40.840 --> 26:43.843
[gasps]
I love seeing you smile.

26:43.878 --> 26:45.569
You can line 'em all up.

26:45.604 --> 26:47.502
[kids' music playing]

26:47.536 --> 26:51.230
Yes.
Oh, I would love to sit closer.

26:54.129 --> 26:55.579
It's pretty cool in here, huh?

26:55.614 --> 26:56.684
- Yeah.

26:56.718 --> 26:57.995
- Yeah.

26:59.721 --> 27:02.137
[keys jangle, door opens]

27:02.172 --> 27:05.969
- Oh, good, you're not dead.

27:06.003 --> 27:07.798
- I'm sorry.
- Not good enough.

27:07.833 --> 27:10.594
I've spent the last 36 hours
imagining you bleeding out

27:10.629 --> 27:12.423
at a variety
of Los Angeles landmarks.

27:12.458 --> 27:14.149
- I would have called you
if I could.

27:14.184 --> 27:18.015
- Telling me you're alive
is not optional.

27:18.050 --> 27:21.260
What the hell are you into
that's making you so crazy?

27:21.294 --> 27:23.020
- I can't tell you.
- Why?

27:23.055 --> 27:24.366
- Because even knowing about it
would put you at risk

27:24.401 --> 27:25.782
with the department.

27:28.198 --> 27:29.268
- You committed a crime?

27:29.302 --> 27:31.166
- No.

27:31.201 --> 27:32.651
I mean, no, not--
not technically.

27:32.685 --> 27:34.583
- But you've done something
that I would be compelled

27:34.618 --> 27:36.413
to report, and if I didn't,
I would get disciplined?

27:36.447 --> 27:37.966
- I'm not gonna have
my drama infect you.

27:38.001 --> 27:39.140
- Then what are you doing here?

27:39.174 --> 27:40.659
[soft dramatic music]

27:40.693 --> 27:41.660
- I-I came to see you.

27:41.694 --> 27:43.834
- And what?

27:43.869 --> 27:45.215
Order take-in?
Watch TV?

27:45.249 --> 27:46.561
Pretend like
nothing's going on?

27:46.595 --> 27:47.907
- No. I--

27:47.942 --> 27:50.669
- If you are not here
to tell me the truth...

27:50.703 --> 27:53.913
♪

27:53.948 --> 27:56.019
I need you to leave.

28:00.782 --> 28:02.059
- Understood.

28:02.094 --> 28:08.652
♪

28:08.687 --> 28:11.206
- Hey, how are we doing
on the multiple homicides?

28:11.241 --> 28:12.863
- Yeah, we're coming up
empty so far.

28:12.898 --> 28:15.245
- No eyewitnesses,
not a lot of doorbell cameras

28:15.279 --> 28:16.522
in that neighborhood.
- Yeah, and we talked

28:16.556 --> 28:18.351
to some coworkers,
and they did confirm

28:18.386 --> 28:19.698
that they had turned
their lives around.

28:19.732 --> 28:21.078
[device beeps]

28:21.113 --> 28:23.011
- Now a dead end on ballistics.

28:23.046 --> 28:25.151
No match.

28:25.186 --> 28:26.532
No hits on any of the prints.

28:26.566 --> 28:28.499
- We should expand
the canvassing area.

28:28.534 --> 28:30.605
I'll add some units,
widen the grid.

28:31.917 --> 28:33.401
- Wait, uh,

28:33.435 --> 28:35.990
it looks like the Hughes
got a payment

28:36.024 --> 28:39.062
every third of the month
for $300

28:39.096 --> 28:40.753
like clockwork.

28:40.788 --> 28:42.134
- Drug payments?

28:42.168 --> 28:43.514
Maybe the dad got back
in the game.

28:43.549 --> 28:45.206
- You know a lot of junkies
on a payment plan?

28:45.240 --> 28:47.104
- So...what?

28:48.623 --> 28:50.832
- Rent check?

28:50.867 --> 28:52.696
I mean, they have had
money problems.

28:52.731 --> 28:54.422
And that back room
felt different

28:54.456 --> 28:55.526
than the rest of the house.

28:55.561 --> 28:57.045
There were no personal items,

28:57.080 --> 28:59.392
and it had a dead bolt on it.

28:59.427 --> 29:01.015
Maybe they took on a tenant.

29:01.049 --> 29:02.499
- A tenant that disappears

29:02.533 --> 29:04.190
after an entire family
is slaughtered.

29:04.225 --> 29:05.847
- Looks like we have a suspect.

29:14.200 --> 29:15.581
- Hey, I need your help

29:15.615 --> 29:17.169
figuring out what's
going on with Tim.

29:17.203 --> 29:18.826
- Good morning.
- Morning.

29:18.860 --> 29:20.689
Hi, how are you?
I'm fine. Thanks.

29:20.724 --> 29:22.174
Um, that's a lie.

29:22.208 --> 29:25.142
Okay, so two nights ago,

29:25.177 --> 29:27.662
Tim got this crazy phone call
and then he disappeared.

29:27.696 --> 29:29.664
Then he called in sick.

29:29.698 --> 29:31.597
And now he says that
if he tells me what's going on,

29:31.631 --> 29:33.219
I could get fired.

29:33.254 --> 29:34.773
- Well, then I--
I guess it's a good thing

29:34.807 --> 29:36.602
he didn't tell you.

29:36.636 --> 29:38.915
- Would you accept
that reasoning from Bailey?

29:38.949 --> 29:40.571
- No.
- Look, if I knew what was

29:40.606 --> 29:42.815
going on, maybe I could help--
we could help.

29:42.850 --> 29:43.954
- Right.
But if he won't tell you,

29:43.989 --> 29:45.645
I don't see what choice
you have.

29:45.680 --> 29:47.371
[car door closes]

29:47.406 --> 29:49.373
What's going on?
- We ID'd the guy renting

29:49.408 --> 29:50.961
the back bedroom
from the Hughes.

29:50.996 --> 29:52.135
- Midnight shift
brought him in.

29:52.169 --> 29:53.826
- Uh, I have to--
- N-no, of course.

29:53.861 --> 29:54.965
Good luck.
- Okay, you too.

29:55.000 --> 29:56.518
And I'm here if you need me.

30:00.626 --> 30:04.354
- All right, we got warm milk,
sound machine.

30:04.388 --> 30:07.012
We are ready for nap.

30:10.360 --> 30:11.913
Anna?

30:13.742 --> 30:15.158
Anna?

30:15.192 --> 30:17.056
[unsettling music]

30:17.091 --> 30:19.162
Sweetie?
Come on out, sweetie.

30:19.196 --> 30:20.888
We're not playing
hide-and-seek.

30:20.922 --> 30:25.996
♪

30:26.031 --> 30:27.826
Anna?

30:27.860 --> 30:31.070
[breathing heavily]

30:31.105 --> 30:32.416
Anna?

30:34.936 --> 30:37.076
Anna. Honey.

30:39.009 --> 30:40.114
[groans]

30:43.048 --> 30:44.221
Oh, my God.

30:44.256 --> 30:45.222
Where's John?

30:46.914 --> 30:48.881
[line trills]

30:48.916 --> 30:50.124
- Hi, it's John Nolan.

30:50.158 --> 30:51.125
Leave a message at the beep.

30:51.159 --> 30:52.195
[voicemail beeps]

30:53.713 --> 30:55.267
- Anna, sweetie.

30:57.890 --> 30:59.719
- [coos]
- [gasps]

30:59.754 --> 31:02.136
Oh, sweetie.

31:02.170 --> 31:03.965
You had me so scared.

31:04.000 --> 31:05.760
Oh, come here.

31:05.794 --> 31:09.177
Oh, sweetie, I was so scared.

31:09.212 --> 31:11.145
Okay.

31:11.179 --> 31:13.975
Oh, it's kind of nice in here.

31:14.010 --> 31:15.804
I actually get why you like it.

31:20.085 --> 31:21.396
- Where were you
night before last?

31:21.431 --> 31:22.984
- Uh, I was at home
with my wife.

31:23.019 --> 31:24.641
You can call her.
She'll tell you.

31:24.675 --> 31:27.920
- What's your relationship
to the Hughes?

31:27.955 --> 31:29.888
- Ellis and I go way back.

31:29.922 --> 31:32.304
Uh, I work in Brentwood,
live in Victorville.

31:32.338 --> 31:34.064
It's about a two-hour drive
on a good day.

31:34.099 --> 31:36.032
I rent a room from them
on the nights that I work late.

31:37.550 --> 31:39.173
But I swear,
I would never hurt them.

31:39.207 --> 31:41.175
- You know what happened?

31:41.209 --> 31:43.418
- It's all over the news.

31:43.453 --> 31:44.833
Is Anna okay?

31:44.868 --> 31:45.938
- She's safe.

31:49.079 --> 31:51.081
- Look, I--I know
I should have came forward

31:51.116 --> 31:53.394
and said something, but, look,

31:53.428 --> 31:55.223
I saw what he did to them,
and I was scared.

31:55.258 --> 31:56.742
- He?

31:56.776 --> 31:58.986
- Yeah, Bad Rod.

31:59.020 --> 32:00.401
[sighs]

32:00.435 --> 32:03.576
Ellis won a lottery ticket
a couple days ago,

32:03.611 --> 32:06.959
was bragging how he hit big,
and Rod seemed real interested.

32:06.994 --> 32:08.927
[intriguing music]

32:08.961 --> 32:10.756
- I couldn't find her.

32:10.790 --> 32:13.069
And suddenly, I was 15 again,

32:13.103 --> 32:15.554
and that little boy
was face down in the pool.

32:15.588 --> 32:17.349
I can't believe I ever thought
I could do this.

32:19.109 --> 32:22.147
- I understand how that trauma
could imprint on you.

32:22.181 --> 32:24.735
But that little boy was okay,

32:24.770 --> 32:25.978
and so is Anna.

32:26.013 --> 32:28.774
- I am terrified
I'm gonna fail her.

32:28.808 --> 32:30.120
- We all are.

32:30.155 --> 32:32.571
One time, I accidentally
slammed Dominique's finger

32:32.605 --> 32:34.331
in the sliding glass door.

32:34.366 --> 32:36.920
I can still hear her scream.
- Mm.

32:36.955 --> 32:38.680
- You don't have to be perfect

32:38.715 --> 32:40.751
to take care
of this little girl.

32:40.786 --> 32:43.340
You just have to care enough

32:43.375 --> 32:46.378
to get through
the scary moments.

32:46.412 --> 32:49.588
But I can take her with me,
if you want.

32:49.622 --> 32:51.555
No judgment whatsoever.

32:55.904 --> 32:58.010
- No. Let her sleep.

33:00.116 --> 33:01.945
- You got this.

33:01.980 --> 33:03.567
- A lottery ticket?

33:03.602 --> 33:05.362
That's why he killed
that little girl's family?

33:05.397 --> 33:08.331
- Not even a lottery ticket,
a scratch-off for $1,500.

33:08.365 --> 33:11.023
- If he's willing to kill
three people for $1,500,

33:11.058 --> 33:12.542
what's he gonna do
to stay out of prison?

33:12.576 --> 33:15.407
- All right, Nolan, Juarez,
you two cover the back.

33:15.441 --> 33:17.478
You three take the front.

33:17.512 --> 33:19.135
If he doesn't go quietly,
we hold the perimeter

33:19.169 --> 33:20.412
and let SWAT do their thing.

33:20.446 --> 33:21.378
All right, go.

33:48.026 --> 33:49.993
- Mom's probably been searched
a dozen times,

33:50.028 --> 33:51.581
tired of having a gun
stuck in her face.

33:51.615 --> 33:53.548
You wanna low-key this?

33:53.583 --> 33:55.171
- All right,
we're gonna low-key this.

33:55.205 --> 33:57.069
Roderick may not be home,
and we don't want to traumatize

33:57.104 --> 33:58.898
this woman any more
than we have to.

33:58.933 --> 34:00.176
- Roger that.
We're in position.

34:00.210 --> 34:01.694
No movement in the house.

34:10.255 --> 34:11.911
- LAPD. Mrs. Eaves?

34:11.946 --> 34:13.465
- We have a search warrant
for this house

34:13.498 --> 34:16.985
and an arrest warrant
for Roderick Eaves.

34:17.020 --> 34:18.021
- He's not here.

34:18.056 --> 34:19.574
That's what that sign says.

34:19.609 --> 34:21.197
I haven't seen or heard
from him in months.

34:21.231 --> 34:23.475
So don't go tearing up
my house.

34:23.509 --> 34:24.752
- A search warrant
isn't a choice, ma'am.

34:24.786 --> 34:25.822
Please step outside.

34:25.856 --> 34:27.065
[floorboards creak]

34:28.514 --> 34:30.896
- Uh, floor gets creaky
after I vacuum.

34:30.929 --> 34:31.862
- Yeah, that's not a thing.

34:31.897 --> 34:33.761
Come here.

34:33.795 --> 34:35.141
We have movement inside.

34:35.176 --> 34:36.522
Perimeter hold.
We are making entry.

34:37.902 --> 34:42.010
[thunderous gunshots]

34:42.045 --> 34:42.873
What the hell is he shooting?

34:42.908 --> 34:44.978
- High-velocity slug rounds.

34:45.013 --> 34:46.532
Control, we have
a barricaded suspect

34:46.567 --> 34:48.051
with some type of long gun.

34:48.085 --> 34:49.501
Send SWAT to our location.

34:49.534 --> 34:50.847
[gunshots continue]

34:50.880 --> 34:52.882
[car alarms blaring,
dogs barking]

34:52.918 --> 34:55.402
- I got an open window.
You want tear gas?

34:55.438 --> 34:56.438
- Do it.

35:00.684 --> 35:03.653
[dramatic music]

35:03.687 --> 35:07.691
♪

35:07.726 --> 35:08.727
- Cover me.

35:13.973 --> 35:20.601
♪

35:26.262 --> 35:27.677
[gunshot]

35:27.711 --> 35:34.442
♪

35:35.857 --> 35:39.033
- [groaning]

35:43.348 --> 35:44.590
- Clear.

35:46.385 --> 35:47.869
Control, Code 4.

35:47.904 --> 35:49.181
We have suspect in custody.

35:49.216 --> 35:52.011
Mobilize an RA unit for a GSW.

35:52.046 --> 35:52.805
- All right.
Everyone okay?

35:52.840 --> 35:54.186
- All in one piece.

35:59.053 --> 36:00.296
- Hey, hey.
You okay?

36:00.330 --> 36:01.918
Heard it got a little dicey
out there today.

36:01.952 --> 36:03.506
- Oh, yeah.
A bit of a soup sandwich,

36:03.540 --> 36:05.197
but we all came out all right.

36:05.232 --> 36:06.164
- All over
a scratch-off ticket?

36:06.198 --> 36:07.751
- Yeah.
- [chuckles]

36:07.786 --> 36:09.477
Oh, hey, I got
some good news for you.

36:09.512 --> 36:11.065
- Oscar died?

36:11.099 --> 36:12.894
- You have to stop
joking like that.

36:12.929 --> 36:13.999
- Even though he stabbed you?

36:14.033 --> 36:15.414
- Yeah, fair enough.

36:15.449 --> 36:17.209
A judge granted
the motion to dismiss.

36:17.244 --> 36:19.315
- So it's over?
- For you.

36:19.349 --> 36:21.213
The judge said you had
the lowest tier of culpability.

36:21.248 --> 36:22.835
The sheriff stationed
outside the hospital room

36:22.870 --> 36:25.044
was primarily responsible
for Oscar's safety.

36:25.079 --> 36:26.218
- Wesley, that is great.
- Yeah.

36:26.253 --> 36:27.875
- Thank you.
- I'd say get some sleep,

36:27.909 --> 36:29.083
but I know you got a toddler

36:29.117 --> 36:30.222
at your house, so--
- Oh, yeah, no.

36:30.257 --> 36:31.016
Sleep is out the window.
- Ooh, yeah.

36:32.914 --> 36:35.054
- I need to clear the air
on something.

36:35.089 --> 36:37.885
Um, look, the other night--

36:37.919 --> 36:39.197
- Totally my fault.

36:39.231 --> 36:41.337
I should never have said yes
to that drink.

36:41.371 --> 36:43.822
It was a violation of
our professional relationships,

36:43.856 --> 36:46.238
and I could get
into a lot of trouble.

36:46.273 --> 36:48.378
- T-trust me, you won't.
I would never narc you out.

36:48.413 --> 36:50.173
- I know that,
but I never should have

36:50.208 --> 36:52.658
put you in a position
to make that choice.

36:52.693 --> 36:55.074
I understand if you want
to switch therapists.

36:55.109 --> 36:56.248
- No.

36:56.283 --> 36:58.077
No, not at all.

36:58.112 --> 37:01.460
Look, you are the first person

37:01.495 --> 37:04.291
that I've ever felt
comfortable opening up to,

37:04.325 --> 37:06.638
and I can't lose that.

37:06.672 --> 37:08.295
You know, so no matter the--

37:08.329 --> 37:10.331
the physical attraction
we felt--

37:10.366 --> 37:12.713
- Aaron.

37:12.747 --> 37:16.510
I need to make this very clear.

37:16.544 --> 37:20.652
There was and is no attraction
on my end.

37:20.686 --> 37:22.101
I need you to understand that.

37:24.138 --> 37:26.174
- Understood. Yeah.

37:26.209 --> 37:29.074
Uh, glad we cleared the air
on that.

37:29.108 --> 37:31.249
[clears throat]
See you next session.

37:31.283 --> 37:32.250
- Have a good week.

37:32.284 --> 37:33.872
- Thank you.
You too.

37:33.906 --> 37:36.737
[door opens and closes]

37:36.771 --> 37:39.326
[Mallrat's "Teeth"]

37:39.360 --> 37:40.327
[camera beeps]

37:40.361 --> 37:45.263
♪

37:45.297 --> 37:47.679
- What are you doing?

37:47.713 --> 37:49.888
- Nothing.
I am not calling,

37:49.922 --> 37:52.822
not searching, not stalking.

37:52.856 --> 37:56.826
I'm just being a good
girlfriend and trusting my man.

37:56.860 --> 37:59.277
- Worst country song ever.

37:59.311 --> 38:00.554
Still no word?

38:00.588 --> 38:01.727
- I mean, we talked last night.

38:01.762 --> 38:03.211
- That's good.

38:03.246 --> 38:04.972
- More like I got heated
and he just stood there,

38:05.006 --> 38:06.560
so I don't know.

38:06.594 --> 38:08.182
I'm at a loss.
- I've got an idea.

38:08.216 --> 38:09.839
Let's put a tracker
on his truck.

38:09.873 --> 38:12.324
- You--you are
a bad influence.

38:12.359 --> 38:13.912
- No. You're just
a really good teacher.

38:13.946 --> 38:15.534
- Wh-what?

38:15.569 --> 38:16.984
- You think I haven't learned
a thing or two

38:17.018 --> 38:19.020
living with a cop
who aced undercover school?

38:19.055 --> 38:21.402
- Okay.
What have you learned?

38:21.437 --> 38:23.024
- Never hold your coffee
with your gun hand.

38:23.059 --> 38:24.819
- Yes, that is actually
very useful.

38:24.854 --> 38:26.200
However, you do not have a gun.

38:26.234 --> 38:27.339
So what else?

38:27.374 --> 38:28.892
- Keep your head on a swivel.

38:28.927 --> 38:30.238
- What is this?

38:30.273 --> 38:31.826
- Oh, balance.
- [laughs]

38:31.861 --> 38:32.827
Good.

38:32.862 --> 38:38.523
♪

38:38.557 --> 38:42.354
- ♪ In my prayer,
I don't speak ♪

38:42.389 --> 38:47.221
♪ But with my hands
and on my knees ♪

38:47.255 --> 38:51.570
♪ When I ask, I receive

38:51.605 --> 38:55.471
♪ Don't play fair,
don't be sweet ♪

38:55.505 --> 39:00.268
♪ It's in the air
that I breathe ♪

39:00.303 --> 39:04.342
♪ Understand it's
up my sleeve ♪

39:04.376 --> 39:09.001
♪ Well, in my head,
it's in my sleep ♪

39:09.036 --> 39:12.073
♪ With my hands, in my teeth

39:12.108 --> 39:13.454
- Oh, my gosh.

39:13.489 --> 39:15.214
I love what you've done here.

39:15.249 --> 39:18.494
I see a pig,
but I also see a cat.

39:18.528 --> 39:20.875
More of a pig-cat.

39:20.910 --> 39:22.394
Kind of brilliant.

39:22.429 --> 39:23.395
She's brilliant.

39:23.430 --> 39:24.223
- Okay.

39:25.604 --> 39:26.536
- Pardon me.

39:28.607 --> 39:29.884
- Let's do it.

39:29.919 --> 39:31.886
- Do what?
- Foster her.

39:31.921 --> 39:33.509
I know we decided not
to have kids,

39:33.543 --> 39:35.096
but this feels like fate.

39:35.131 --> 39:36.512
- Yeah. No, it does.

39:36.546 --> 39:38.065
Are y--are you sure
you're all right with this?

39:38.099 --> 39:40.101
- Yeah.
I-I-I mean, I'm terrified,

39:40.136 --> 39:41.586
but I can run
into burning buildings.

39:41.620 --> 39:42.897
[knock on door]
I can do this.

39:42.932 --> 39:44.347
- Of course you can.
This is gonna be great.

39:44.382 --> 39:45.797
- Yes.
- This is gonna be so great.

39:45.831 --> 39:47.833
- Yes.

39:47.868 --> 39:50.042
both: Hi.
- Come in.

39:50.077 --> 39:52.044
Hi.
- Great news.

39:52.079 --> 39:53.701
John, Bailey,
this is Don Hughes,

39:53.736 --> 39:55.323
Anna's uncle from Tampa.

39:55.358 --> 39:57.222
- Oh, great to meet you.
